nuous account of the island's past. In attempting to fuse the radically new Galfridian account of the past with that of the conventional twelfth-century (Bedan) view, Alfred's use and manipulation of his sources is highly revealing and suggests a quite critical reception of Geoffrey's history, a mindset which by the end of the twelfth century appears almost entirely to have disappeared amongst chroniclers.Alfred's history is also an important, and presently undervalued, witness to the reception and dissemination of three of the most important Anglo-Norman histories: Symeon of Durham Historia Regum, The Chronicle of John of Worcester and Henry of Huntingdon, Historia Anglorum, from which works it borrows extensively. In the manner of use of these sources, the author tells us much about the ecclesiastical and intellectual interests and outlook of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Norman.  aBrutus.  aGeoffrey of Monmouth.  aHenry I.  aHenry of Huntingdon.  aHistoria Anglorum.  aHistoria Regum.  aHistory of the Kings of Britain.  aSymeon of Durham.  aThe Chronicle of John of Worcester.1 aLockyer, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlevin, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800108967?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800108967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800108967/original  a978-3-11-142849-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles